#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""caj -- online (Mac-side) job builder + signer for the air-gapped Nebula CA
harness.

caj reads a simple job SPEC file plus staged payload files (host pubkeys, a
run-script's script file, ...), assembles the wire-format `manifest.json`
+ `payload/` bundle, packs it into `job.tar` with clean member names, signs
it with `ssh-keygen -Y sign` (Ed25519, namespace causb.config.NS ==
"nebula-ca-job" -- the same namespace causb.verify checks against), and
writes both `job.tar` and `job.tar.sig` to `<stick>/inbox/`. This is the ONLY
half of the wire contract caj is responsible for: the box-side verify/
extract/dispatch/commit pipeline (causb.extract, causb.commitlog, ...) is
implemented and tested entirely on the box.

**`--breakglass <key>` (break-glass co-signature).** A privileged/
break-glass-touching job (e.g. a `rotate-job-signers` job that changes
`breakglass_signers`, or a `privileged` run-script) needs a SECOND detached
signature from the offline break-glass key, alongside the operator's primary
signature -- the box already gates on this (`causb.verify.verify_cosign`).
When `--breakglass <key>` is given, build_command ALSO signs the SAME
job.tar bytes with that key, in the SAME `nebula-ca-job` namespace, and
delivers the result as `<stick>/inbox/job.tar.bg.sig` alongside `job.tar` +
`job.tar.sig` (see `_sign_breakglass` and `_deliver_atomic`). Without
`--breakglass`, behavior is entirely unchanged -- no `job.tar.bg.sig` is ever
produced, and a job that actually needed a co-signature correctly fails the
box's `cosign_required` gate instead of silently going out uncosigned.

**Platform note -- why caj imports only causb.config and causb.manifest.**
caj's production runtime is the operator's Mac (macOS), not the air-gapped
Linux box. `causb.extract.extract()` drives a raw Linux-only
`openat2` syscall (hardcoded syscall number 437) via ctypes -- meaningless,
and unsafe to invoke, on Darwin. caj therefore never imports causb.extract
(or causb.collect/causb.commitlog/causb.freshness, which are equally
box-only in scope). Its own guarantee that job.tar's member names are clean
(no leading "./", no absolute path, no "..", depth <= causb.config.CAPS
["depth"]) comes from constructing every tar member with an explicit,
already-safe `arcname=` (see `_build_job_tar`), not from re-running the
box's hardened extractor locally. What caj DOES call, as a portable,
pure-Python (json/uuid only) self-check before ever touching the USB stick,
is `causb.manifest.parse()` on the manifest bytes it is about to sign --
if the box's own strict parser would reject this manifest, caj
refuses to sign it, rather than silently producing a bundle the box will
later bounce. causb.verify.verify() is NOT called by caj itself for
the same portability reason (it doesn't need an allowed_signers file to
build a job, and the Mac -- outside the trust boundary -- has no
business holding a copy of the box's trust anchor); it is the box, and this
project's own test suite, that verify a caj-produced signature.

**Spec file format.** Plain "key: value" lines (no PyYAML, no eval -- only
str.partition(":")). Blank lines and lines starting with "#" are ignored.
Reserved top-level keys:

  name        optional human-readable label -> manifest bundle_id (falls
              back to the job_id if omitted).
  operation   required -> jobs[0].operation (e.g. "sign-hosts", "run-script").
  box         optional, defaults to causb.config.BOX_NAME -> jobs[0]'s
              manifest.box.
  payload     optional comma-separated list of STAGED file basenames (e.g.
              "alice.pub,bob.pub") -> jobs[0].payload. Each name is resolved
              relative to the spec file's OWN directory (the natural
              "staging area": an operator drops a spec file next to the
              pubkeys/script it references), must be a plain basename
              (no "/", not "." or ".."), and may appear at most ONCE -- a
              duplicate basename is a rejected operator typo, not a silently
              doubled (and box-rejected) tar member.
  entrypoint  optional -> jobs[0].entrypoint (must be one of `payload`'s
              names for operation=="run-script"; caj checks this itself,
              ahead of the identical check inside causb.manifest.parse(),
              purely for a clearer CLI error message).

Any OTHER key of the form `args.<name>: <value>` populates
jobs[0].args[<name>] = <value> -- a plain string in every case except one:
an `args.<name>` value of exactly `true` or `false` is emitted as a JSON
boolean; every other value is a string. The match is case-sensitive and
exact -- `True`, `TRUE`, `yes`, `1`, and any value merely containing
"true"/"false" as a substring (e.g. a value with leading/trailing content)
are all left as plain strings, same as before. This is the ONLY coercion
`_parse_spec` performs: no numbers, no `null`, nothing else is ever
special-cased -- e.g. `args.groups: admins` or `args.duration: 8760h` stay
strings, and a value with a comma (such as multiple nebula groups) is left
as one comma-joined string rather than split into a JSON list, since that
is exactly the shape nebula-cert's own `-groups` flag already expects.

This narrow coercion exists for exactly two args, both booleans the box
itself requires be a REAL JSON boolean, never a truthy string
(a truthy string must never grant privilege) -- `causb.dispatch.
_is_privileged` requires `args["privileged"] is True` before a `run-script`
may run as root (and additionally requires a break-glass co-signature,
`--breakglass`, or the box refuses `cosign_failed`), and `box/handlers/
rotate-ca` requires `isinstance(args["compromise"], bool)`. Before this
coercion existed, EVERY `args.<name>` value -- including these two -- was
stored as a plain string, so `args.privileged: true` reached the box as the
STRING `"true"`: both strict checks correctly refused it (fail-SAFE -- never
MORE privilege than intended), but that made a privileged run-script and a
`rotate-ca --compromise` literally unreachable via caj (the gap this
coercion closes). `causb.manifest.parse()` places no constraint on
args' internal shape at all (not even that it exists), so this mapping --
including which two values get coerced -- is a pure caj convention, not a
wire-contract requirement; a future third boolean arg would need the exact
same `true`/`false` spelling to get the same treatment.

**seq bookkeeping ("seq = max(repo ca-state/last-seq,
highest-built-unconfirmed)+1").** Two small counter files live in a
`ca-state/` directory (by default `<repo_root>/ca-state/`, i.e. a sibling of
this script's own `mac/` directory -- overridable via the `CAJ_STATE_DIR`
environment variable, used by this project's own test suite to avoid ever
touching the real repo checkout's ca-state during a test run):

  ca-state/last-seq        the REPO's last box-CONFIRMED seq. This file is
                            written by caj-recv (a separate, later tool) as
                            it reconciles what the box actually reports;
                            caj itself only ever READS it (default 0 if
                            absent -- a fresh repo has no confirmed history).
  ca-state/last-built-seq   caj's OWN simple local counter: "the highest seq
                            caj has built so far, whether or not it has been
                            confirmed yet" -- exactly the spec's
                            "highest-built-unconfirmed" tracking, kept as
                            deliberately simple as the spec invites: a
                            single integer file, bumped by caj after EVERY
                            successful build (including a --retry).

Each `build` computes `seq = max(last-seq, last-built-seq) + 1` and -- BEFORE
building, signing, or delivering anything -- persists that value back to
`last-built-seq` (the "reservation"), all under the single flock. Reserving
up front is what makes delivery crash-safe: a crash or failure ANYWHERE in
the build/sign/deliver that follows can at worst WASTE the reserved seq --
the box only requires a monotonically INCREASING `seq` (`seq > last
committed`), so a gap in the sequence is harmless -- and, critically, no two
DELIVERED jobs can ever bear the same seq. (An earlier revision recorded the
seq only AFTER copying the job onto the stick; that left a crash window
between "job delivered" and "seq recorded" in which the next build would
REUSE the seq and strand the already-delivered, legitimately-signed job as
`stale_seq` at the box -- reproduced in review, now fixed.) A deterministic
pre-delivery failure (e.g. a manifest self-check rejection) likewise merely
wastes the reserved seq, which is preferable to reintroducing any window in
which a delivered job's seq could be reused. Both
files are read/written with the same plain "read int, default 0 if absent" /
"atomic tmp-then-rename" convention causb.commitlog/causb.freshness use for
their own box-side seq state, for consistency across the codebase -- though
unlike that box-side state (which must be crash-atomic), this
Mac-side bookkeeping is not itself safety-critical (nothing downstream ever
trusts THESE files' bytes; the box only ever trusts the seq baked into a
signed manifest), so no fsync is performed here, only a plain atomic
os.replace().

**--retry <job_id>.** Reuses the given job_id verbatim (validated as a
syntactically well-formed uuid4 -- causb.manifest.parse()'s own `_is_uuid4`
check, exercised via the pre-sign self-check, is still the final authority)
instead of minting a fresh uuid4, but goes through the exact same seq
computation as any other build -- so a retried job still "advances seq"
(a re-delivery of an already-committed job_id must go through a NEW
seq to not appear stale to the box's freshness check, while the box's own
commit-log replays the ORIGINAL cached bytes for that job_id rather than
re-running anything).

**job.tar construction ("CLEAN member names ONLY").** Built via
`tarfile.open(path, "w")` with an explicit `arcname=` per file -- exactly
"manifest.json" and "payload/<basename>" for each staged payload file. This
project never calls `tar.add(directory)` (which can introduce a "./"-rooted
name or a bare directory-type member -- the box's causb.extract rejects any
non-"manifest.json"/"payload/..." shape AND any non-regular-file member,
including a directory entry for "payload" itself) -- only individual,
already-validated-basename files are ever added, one by one.

**Atomic delivery to the stick.** `job.tar` and `job.tar.sig` are placed
into `<stick>/inbox/` each via a temp-name write + `os.replace()` (atomic
within the one inbox directory), with the SIGNATURE delivered LAST. A crash
or USB-yank mid-delivery therefore leaves, at worst, a `job.tar` with no (or
a stale) `job.tar.sig` -- which the box rejects fail-closed (it never acts on
an unsigned or signature-mismatched job) -- never a truncated/partial final
file, and never a signature paired with a missing/truncated tar. When a
`job.tar.bg.sig` is also being delivered (`--breakglass`), it is placed
BETWEEN `job.tar` and `job.tar.sig`: `job.tar` -> `job.tar.bg.sig` ->
`job.tar.sig` (primary sig still LAST). The primary signature is the box's
one completeness signal regardless of whether a co-signature rides along, so
it must remain the final file written -- a crash after the bg.sig but before
the primary sig still leaves the box with no primary `job.tar.sig` to see,
and it fails closed exactly as it would with no break-glass sig at all.

**Single-writer.** All of the above -- reading the two seq counters,
building+signing+placing the job, and bumping last-built-seq -- happens
under one exclusive `fcntl.flock()` on `ca-state/.caj.lock`, so two
concurrent `caj build` invocations (e.g. two terminals) can't race on seq
allocation or interleave writes to the same stick.
"""

import argparse
import fcntl
import json
import os
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
import tarfile
import tempfile
import uuid

SCRIPT_DIR = os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))
REPO_ROOT = os.path.dirname(SCRIPT_DIR)

# causb (box/lib/causb) is this repo's own package, not something installed
# on PATH/site-packages -- caj runs standalone on the operator's Mac with no
# PYTHONPATH set up, so it must find it itself, relative to its own location,
# regardless of the caller's cwd or environment.
sys.path.insert(0, os.path.join(REPO_ROOT, "box", "lib"))

from causb import config  # noqa: E402  (see sys.path.insert above)
from causb import manifest as causb_manifest  # noqa: E402

_LAST_SEQ_NAME = "last-seq"
_LAST_BUILT_SEQ_NAME = "last-built-seq"
_LOCK_NAME = ".caj.lock"


class CajError(Exception):
    """A user-facing caj CLI error: bad spec, missing/unsafe payload entry,
    a manifest that would fail the box's own parser, a signing failure, ...
    Caught once at main() and reported to stderr with exit code 1 -- never a
    raw traceback for one of these expected, nameable failure modes."""


# --- spec file parsing ---


def _coerce_arg_value(value: str):
    """An `args.<name>` value of exactly `true` or `false` is emitted as a
    JSON boolean; every other value is a string (module docstring's
    `args.<name>` convention). Case-sensitive, exact-match only: `True`,
    `TRUE`, `yes`, `1`, `truthy`, and anything else are all left as plain
    strings unchanged -- the box has exactly two boolean args
    (`privileged`, `compromise`), and an operator who genuinely wants the
    literal string "true" is not a real case for either of them, so nothing
    beyond this exact pair of literals is ever coerced (no numbers, no
    `null`, nothing else)."""
    if value == "true":
        return True
    if value == "false":
        return False
    return value


def _parse_spec(spec_path: str) -> dict:
    """Parse a job spec file: plain "key: value" lines, blank lines and
    "#"-comments ignored. See module docstring for the reserved top-level
    keys (name/operation/box/payload/entrypoint) and the `args.<name>`
    convention. Returns a dict with `payload` already split into a
    validated list of basenames and `args` collected into its own nested
    dict; every other reserved key is a plain string (or absent). An
    `args.<name>` value of exactly `true` or `false` is emitted as a JSON
    boolean; every other value is a string (see `_coerce_arg_value`).
    """
    fields = {"args": {}}
    try:
        spec_file = open(spec_path)
    except OSError as exc:
        raise CajError(f"cannot read spec file {spec_path!r}: {exc}")

    with spec_file:
        for lineno, raw_line in enumerate(spec_file, start=1):
            line = raw_line.strip()
            if not line or line.startswith("#"):
                continue
            if ":" not in line:
                raise CajError(
                    f"{spec_path}:{lineno}: expected 'key: value', got {raw_line!r}"
                )
            key, _, value = line.partition(":")
            key = key.strip()
            value = value.strip()
            if not key:
                raise CajError(f"{spec_path}:{lineno}: empty key")
            if key.startswith("args."):
                fields["args"][key[len("args."):]] = _coerce_arg_value(value)
            else:
                fields[key] = value

    if "operation" not in fields:
        raise CajError(f"spec file {spec_path!r} is missing required 'operation'")
    fields.setdefault("box", config.BOX_NAME)
    fields.setdefault("entrypoint", None)

    payload_raw = fields.get("payload", "")
    payload_names = [entry.strip() for entry in payload_raw.split(",") if entry.strip()]
    for name in payload_names:
        if "/" in name or name in (".", ".."):
            raise CajError(f"payload entry is not a safe basename: {name!r}")
    duplicates = sorted({n for n in payload_names if payload_names.count(n) > 1})
    if duplicates:
        # A duplicate basename (e.g. "payload: alice.pub,alice.pub") would
        # otherwise emit two identical payload/<name> tar members -- a wasteful,
        # malformed artifact from a plain operator typo. Reject it up front with
        # a clear message rather than silently doubling the member.
        raise CajError(
            f"duplicate payload basename(s): {', '.join(duplicates)} -- each "
            f"staged file may be listed in 'payload' only once"
        )
    fields["payload"] = payload_names

    if fields["operation"] == "run-script":
        if not fields["entrypoint"] or fields["entrypoint"] not in payload_names:
            raise CajError(
                "operation=run-script requires 'entrypoint' to name one of "
                "the 'payload' files"
            )

    return fields


def _resolve_payload_sources(spec_path: str, payload_names: list) -> list:
    """Resolve each staged payload basename to an actual file on disk,
    relative to the spec file's OWN directory (see module docstring)."""
    spec_dir = os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(spec_path))
    sources = []
    for name in payload_names:
        src = os.path.join(spec_dir, name)
        if not os.path.isfile(src):
            raise CajError(f"payload file not found (expected staged next to spec): {src}")
        sources.append(src)
    return sources


# --- seq bookkeeping (ca-state/last-seq, ca-state/last-built-seq) ---


def _state_dir() -> str:
    override = os.environ.get("CAJ_STATE_DIR")
    if override:
        return override
    return os.path.join(REPO_ROOT, "ca-state")


def _read_int(path: str, default: int) -> int:
    try:
        with open(path) as f:
            return int(f.read().strip())
    except FileNotFoundError:
        return default


def _write_int_atomic(path: str, value: int) -> None:
    tmp_path = path + ".tmp"
    with open(tmp_path, "w") as f:
        f.write(str(value))
    os.replace(tmp_path, path)


def _next_seq(state_dir: str) -> int:
    """seq = max(repo_last_seq, highest_built_unconfirmed) + 1 (module
    docstring's "seq bookkeeping" section)."""
    repo_last_seq = _read_int(os.path.join(state_dir, _LAST_SEQ_NAME), default=0)
    last_built = _read_int(os.path.join(state_dir, _LAST_BUILT_SEQ_NAME), default=0)
    return max(repo_last_seq, last_built) + 1


def _record_built_seq(state_dir: str, seq: int) -> None:
    _write_int_atomic(os.path.join(state_dir, _LAST_BUILT_SEQ_NAME), seq)


def _with_lock(state_dir: str, fn):
    """Single-writer: run `fn()` (no args) under an exclusive flock on
    `<state_dir>/.caj.lock`, creating state_dir first if needed."""
    os.makedirs(state_dir, exist_ok=True)
    lock_path = os.path.join(state_dir, _LOCK_NAME)
    lock_fd = os.open(lock_path, os.O_CREAT | os.O_RDWR, 0o600)
    try:
        fcntl.flock(lock_fd, fcntl.LOCK_EX)
        return fn()
    finally:
        fcntl.flock(lock_fd, fcntl.LOCK_UN)
        os.close(lock_fd)


# --- job_id (fresh uuid4, or --retry's preserved one) ---


def _resolve_job_id(retry_job_id: str) -> str:
    if retry_job_id is None:
        return str(uuid.uuid4())
    try:
        parsed = uuid.UUID(retry_job_id)
    except (ValueError, AttributeError, TypeError):
        raise CajError(f"--retry job_id is not a valid uuid: {retry_job_id!r}")
    if parsed.version != 4:
        raise CajError(f"--retry job_id is not a uuid4: {retry_job_id!r}")
    return retry_job_id


# --- manifest + job.tar assembly ---


def _build_manifest(spec: dict, box: str, seq: int, job_id: str) -> dict:
    return {
        "schema_version": 1,
        "bundle_id": spec.get("name") or job_id,
        "box": box,
        "seq": seq,
        "jobs": [
            {
                "job_id": job_id,
                "operation": spec["operation"],
                "args": spec["args"],
                "payload": spec["payload"],
                "entrypoint": spec["entrypoint"],
            }
        ],
    }


def _self_check_manifest(raw: bytes, payload_names: list) -> None:
    """Refuse to sign a manifest the box's own strict parser would
    reject -- fail fast, on the Mac, with the SAME reason string the box
    would eventually report, rather than producing a bundle that silently
    fails much later at box-verification time."""
    try:
        causb_manifest.parse(raw, payload_names=set(payload_names))
    except causb_manifest.ManifestError as exc:
        raise CajError(
            f"internal error: the manifest caj just built would be rejected "
            f"by causb.manifest.parse() ({exc.reason}); refusing to sign"
        )


def _build_job_tar(build_dir: str, raw_manifest: bytes, payload_names: list,
                    payload_sources: list) -> str:
    """Assemble manifest.json + payload/<basename> under `build_dir` and tar
    them into `build_dir/job.tar` with CLEAN member names only: exactly
    "manifest.json" and "payload/<basename>" per file, via an explicit
    `arcname=` -- never `tar.add(directory)` (module docstring)."""
    manifest_path = os.path.join(build_dir, "manifest.json")
    with open(manifest_path, "wb") as f:
        f.write(raw_manifest)

    payload_dir = os.path.join(build_dir, "payload")
    os.makedirs(payload_dir, exist_ok=True)
    for name, src in zip(payload_names, payload_sources):
        shutil.copyfile(src, os.path.join(payload_dir, name))

    tar_path = os.path.join(build_dir, "job.tar")
    with tarfile.open(tar_path, "w") as tar:
        tar.add(manifest_path, arcname="manifest.json")
        for name in payload_names:
            tar.add(os.path.join(payload_dir, name), arcname=f"payload/{name}")
    return tar_path


def _sign(key_path: str, tar_path: str) -> str:
    """`ssh-keygen -Y sign -f <key_path> -n <causb.config.NS> <tar_path>` ->
    `<tar_path>.sig`, in the same namespace causb.verify checks against."""
    result = subprocess.run(
        ["ssh-keygen", "-Y", "sign", "-f", key_path, "-n", config.NS, tar_path],
        stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL,
        stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
        stderr=subprocess.PIPE,
    )
    if result.returncode != 0:
        raise CajError(
            f"ssh-keygen -Y sign failed (exit {result.returncode}): "
            f"{result.stderr.decode(errors='replace').strip()}"
        )
    return tar_path + ".sig"


def _sign_breakglass(breakglass_key_path: str, tar_path: str) -> str:
    """Produce the break-glass co-signature: a SECOND detached
    signature over the SAME job.tar bytes, via the exact same `_sign()`
    invocation (same namespace, same ssh-keygen flags) as the primary sig --
    just a different key, ending up named `<tar_path>.bg.sig` instead of
    `<tar_path>.sig`.

    `ssh-keygen -Y sign` always names its output `<input file>.sig` (no flag
    to override this), so signing `tar_path` itself a second time would
    overwrite the just-written primary `<tar_path>.sig`. Instead, this signs
    a byte-identical COPY of tar_path named `<tar_path>.bg` -- ssh-keygen's
    same fixed naming convention then lands the output at exactly
    `<tar_path>.bg.sig`, with no risk of ever clobbering the primary sig (a
    completely different input filename, a completely separate ssh-keygen
    invocation). The SSHSIG format signs only the namespace + a hash of the
    input BYTES, never the input's filename, so this signature verifies
    identically against the real job.tar's bytes (confirmed against
    causb.verify.verify(), which feeds tar_path's bytes on stdin and never
    looks at any filename baked into the signature)."""
    bg_input_path = tar_path + ".bg"
    shutil.copyfile(tar_path, bg_input_path)
    return _sign(breakglass_key_path, bg_input_path)


# --- atomic delivery onto the stick's inbox/ ---


def _place_atomic(src_path: str, final_path: str) -> None:
    """Copy `src_path` to a `.tmp` sibling of `final_path`, flush+fsync it,
    then `os.replace()` it into `final_path` -- an atomic rename within the
    one inbox directory/filesystem. The final name is only ever created by
    renaming a fully-written temp, so a crash or USB-yank can never leave a
    truncated or partially-written final file at that name."""
    tmp_path = final_path + ".tmp"
    with open(src_path, "rb") as src, open(tmp_path, "wb") as dst:
        shutil.copyfileobj(src, dst)
        dst.flush()
        os.fsync(dst.fileno())
    os.replace(tmp_path, final_path)


def _deliver_atomic(tar_path: str, sig_path: str, inbox_dir: str, bg_sig_path: str = None) -> None:
    """Deliver job.tar, then (if given) job.tar.bg.sig, then job.tar.sig into
    `inbox_dir`, each via `_place_atomic` (tmp -> rename), with the PRIMARY
    SIGNATURE written LAST always (extended for the break-glass
    co-sign). If a crash interrupts delivery, the worst observable state on
    the stick is a job.tar (+ maybe a job.tar.bg.sig) with no (or a stale)
    job.tar.sig -- which the box rejects fail-closed -- never a signature
    paired with a truncated/absent tar, and never a primary sig landing
    before a co-signature that was supposed to accompany it.

    `bg_sig_path` defaults to None: when absent (no --breakglass), delivery
    is exactly the original two-file job.tar-then-job.tar.sig sequence --
    unchanged."""
    _place_atomic(tar_path, os.path.join(inbox_dir, "job.tar"))
    if bg_sig_path is not None:
        _place_atomic(bg_sig_path, os.path.join(inbox_dir, "job.tar.bg.sig"))
    _place_atomic(sig_path, os.path.join(inbox_dir, "job.tar.sig"))


# --- the `build` subcommand ---


def build_command(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:
    spec_path = os.path.abspath(os.path.expanduser(args.spec))
    stick = os.path.abspath(os.path.expanduser(args.stick))
    key_path = os.path.abspath(os.path.expanduser(args.key))
    breakglass_key_path = None
    if args.breakglass:
        breakglass_key_path = os.path.abspath(os.path.expanduser(args.breakglass))

    if not os.path.isdir(stick):
        raise CajError(f"--stick path does not exist or is not a directory: {stick}")
    if not os.path.isfile(key_path):
        raise CajError(f"signing key not found: {key_path}")
    if breakglass_key_path is not None and not os.path.isfile(breakglass_key_path):
        raise CajError(f"break-glass signing key not found: {breakglass_key_path}")

    spec = _parse_spec(spec_path)
    payload_sources = _resolve_payload_sources(spec_path, spec["payload"])
    job_id = _resolve_job_id(args.retry)
    state_dir = _state_dir()

    def _do_build():
        seq = _next_seq(state_dir)
        # Reserve the seq BEFORE building/signing/delivering:
        # persist last-built-seq up front, under the flock, so a crash or
        # failure anywhere below can at worst WASTE this seq (the box only
        # requires a monotonically increasing seq -- gaps are fine), and no two
        # DELIVERED jobs can ever bear the same seq. Recording it only AFTER
        # delivery (the earlier order) left a crash window in which the next
        # build reused the seq and stranded the delivered job as stale_seq.
        _record_built_seq(state_dir, seq)

        manifest = _build_manifest(spec, spec["box"], seq, job_id)
        raw = json.dumps(manifest, indent=2, sort_keys=True).encode()
        _self_check_manifest(raw, spec["payload"])

        inbox_dir = os.path.join(stick, "inbox")
        build_dir = tempfile.mkdtemp(prefix="caj-build-")
        try:
            tar_path = _build_job_tar(build_dir, raw, spec["payload"], payload_sources)
            sig_path = _sign(key_path, tar_path)
            bg_sig_path = None
            if breakglass_key_path is not None:
                bg_sig_path = _sign_breakglass(breakglass_key_path, tar_path)
            os.makedirs(inbox_dir, exist_ok=True)
            _deliver_atomic(tar_path, sig_path, inbox_dir, bg_sig_path=bg_sig_path)
        finally:
            shutil.rmtree(build_dir, ignore_errors=True)

        print(f"caj: built job {job_id} (seq={seq}) -> {inbox_dir}")

    _with_lock(state_dir, _do_build)


def main(argv=None) -> int:
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(prog="caj")
    subparsers = parser.add_subparsers(dest="command", required=True)

    build_parser = subparsers.add_parser(
        "build", help="Build and sign a job bundle onto a USB stick's inbox/."
    )
    build_parser.add_argument("--spec", required=True, help="Path to the job spec file.")
    build_parser.add_argument("--stick", required=True, help="Path to the mounted USB stick.")
    build_parser.add_argument(
        "--retry", metavar="JOB_ID", default=None,
        help="Reuse this exact job_id (still advances seq) instead of minting a new one.",
    )
    build_parser.add_argument(
        "--key", default=os.path.expanduser("~/.ssh/id_ed25519"),
        help="ssh-keygen -Y sign signing key (default: ~/.ssh/id_ed25519).",
    )
    build_parser.add_argument(
        "--breakglass", metavar="BREAKGLASS_KEY", default=None,
        help="Also co-sign job.tar with this break-glass key -> "
             "inbox/job.tar.bg.sig (co-signature for a privileged/ "
             "breakglass-touching job). Omit for an ordinary job: no "
             "job.tar.bg.sig is produced.",
    )

    parsed = parser.parse_args(argv)

    try:
        if parsed.command == "build":
            build_command(parsed)
    except CajError as exc:
        print(f"caj: error: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
        return 1
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main())
